AU  - Kircher, Philipp
AU  - Virág, Gábor
Y1  - 2011/02/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2010.00620.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 85
EP  - 103
VL  - 52
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2010.00620.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We build a theoretical model to study the welfare effects and policy implications of firms? market power in a frictional labor market. The main characteristics of our environment are that wages play a role in allocating labor across firms and the number of agents is finite. The decentralized equilibrium is inefficient and the firms? market power results in the misallocation of workers from the high to the low productivity firms. A minimum wage exacerbates the inefficiencies by forcing the low-productivity firms to increase their wage. Moderate unemployment benefits can increase welfare by improving the workers? outside option.
ER  - 

