T1  - SOCIALLY OPTIMAL SUBSIDIES FOR ENTRY: THE CASE OF MEDICARE PAYMENTS TO HMOs*
AU  - Maruyama, Shiko
Y1  - 2011/02/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2010.00621.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 105
EP  - 129
VL  - 52
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2010.00621.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - The U.S. Medicare program has increased its spending on private Medicare plans in anticipation of larger consumer surplus and higher efficiency. To evaluate the welfare consequences of such policy interventions, I develop an empirical model with endogenous entry. Counterfactual simulation reveals the following: subsidizing HMO entry can be justified to enhance national welfare (no excessive entry); the level of price subsidies in 2008, however, is far beyond the optimal level; and the geographic inconsistency between the subsidies and the Medicare fee-for-service costs is another source of inefficiency. Resolving this geographic inconsistency significantly raises national welfare by restructuring entry.
ER  - 

