SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2010.00626.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In a credence good market, sellers know more about buyers? necessity of the good. Because of this information asymmetry, a selfish seller may exaggerate buyers? necessity of the good. This article investigates how the presence of conscientious experts affects selfish experts? behavior. In a monopoly setting, it shows that the presence of a conscientious expert may result in more fraudulent behavior by the selfish expert. This result holds in a competitive setting.
ER  - 

